commits.commitMessage:
downloads: use external caches

Instead of using a big git repository that contains lots of tarballs,
this change would rely on external CDN services to provided the content.

If a downloads/ directory is present at the root, it is still being
used as top priority.
The idea is to ship downloaded content with the Yocto source tarball
so as to make it possible for people to build Yocto without internet
access.

Resolves: LXSWIREF-544
Change-Id: Ie84a6442fef2d6828c8a5f3ed979223b47d71447
commits.subject: downloads: use external caches

common: clean-up obsolete backports

A few packages & patches have been backported for the previous
Yocto 2.2.

These backports are now obsolete since the versions from poky and
meta-openembedded have more recent versions or/and that already include
the patches.

* busybox: 1.24.1 -> 1.27.2
* glibc: 2.24 -> 2.27
* util-linux: 2.28.1 -> 2.32.1
* e2fsprogs: 1.43 -> 1.43.8
* elfutils: 0.166 -> 0.170
* python: 2.7.12 -> 2.7.14 (+ CVE-2018-1000030-1 & CVE-2018-1000030-2)
* qemu: 2.7.0 -> 2.11.1
* libarchive: 3.2.2 -> 3.3.2
* curl: 7.58.0 -> 7.61.0
* dnsmasq: 2.78 (meta-swi) -> 2.78 (poky)
* zlib: 1.2.11 (meta-swi) -> 1.2.11 (poky)

Resolves: LXSWIREF-1041
Change-Id: Ia9e4e71c93231e3eaf75517e5b2f81b6f2975d12
commits.subject: common: clean-up obsolete backports

commits.commitMessage:
virt: add kernel headers to SDK

This is to make it possible for Legato to build kernel modules through
the toolchain.

I noticed that a few things could be inherited on the mdm9xxx side
so I factorized that in the common include
    meta-swi-mdm9xxx/recipes-kernel/linux-quic/linux-quic.inc

The method to generate the kernel-dev package (kernel content that
ends up in the toolchain) was missing some content.
Since Kbuild files were not included, the kernel would remove the
generated headers when running 'make scripts' during the toolchain
install.

Resolves: LXSWIREF-603
Change-Id: I06a8f16b71f7e484d91ce6754d569b969017b854
commits.subject: virt: add kernel headers to SDK

commits.commitMessage:
meta-swi/common: recipes-devtools: add pimd recipe

This package is needed by the swi BSPs.

pimd is a lightweight stand-alone PIM-SM v2 multicast routing daemon.
It is the original USC (netweb/catarina.usc.edu) implementation of
the protocol, according to RFC 2362.

Protocol Independent Multicast, PIM, allows existing networks
to route IP multicast, regardless of what unicast routing protocol
is in use. It is designed to use the existing routing tables to make
its multicast routing decisions. PIM-SM is suitable for sparsely
located multicast subscribers, for dense mode operation mrouted is
recommended, and for static multicast routing smcroute may be used.

Please see http://troglobit.com/pimd.html for more details.

Signed-off-by: Liming Wang <liming.wang@windriver.com>
commits.subject: meta-swi/common: recipes-devtools: add pimd recipe

meta-swi: add swi meta layer

This meta layer is a common layer that supports all
the BSPs of SierraWireless Inc for yocto.

Please see the README files contained in the individual BSP layers for
BSP-specific information.
